    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1907-02-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1907-02-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="39"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d39">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 3691/48.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Minister for Foreign Affairs of
                            Salvador</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                        State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Translation.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">San Salvador</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1907-02-12">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 12, 1907</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I have had the honor to receive the transcript your excellency was pleased to
                    send me of President Roosevelt’s telegram to the Presidents <pb facs="0767"
                        n="617" xml:id="pg_617"/> of Honduras and Nicaragua interposing his good
                    offices to the end of obtaining a pacific settlement of the difficulties pending
                    between the two Republics, and I am glad to inform your excellency that
                    President Escalon once more addressed Presidents Bonilla and Zelaya to-day,
                    tendering them again his friendly mediation to that purpose.</p>
                <p>With the highest consideration,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Manuel Delgardos.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
